To reduce by one in ten, or ten percent.
It originally referred to the killing of every tenth Roman legionnaire in a mutinous or poorly-performing legion. ''Decimus'', tenth, from ''decem'', ten. 
Today, it is often mis-used in terms of scale to describe the ''destruction of a large part of'', eg: a part greater than a tenth.  Also mis-used in terms of context, as in ''the school funds were decimated by the principal's profligacy.'' 
''tr.v.'' Decimates, decimating, decimated. Fr. ''decimare''